Recognising the power imbalance that exists between junior doctors and consultants, and that upstream feedback will rarely occur organically - it would be interesting to see if such a tool could be a bridge to foster empathy between the two groups. Keen to hear your thoughts!

I ask because much of the discussion here signals to me that there is inadequate opportunity for juniors to give feedback directly to specific consultants (rather than the nebulous ‚Äúsenior staff‚Äù) about issues they have with behaviour that may not be outright inappropriate.
This is an evidence-based mechanism for assessing physician performance, as detailed in this elegant systematic review: https://t.co/TZCT9SbZgo

For those unfamiliar, MSF is a de-identified questionnaire-style assessment that seeks numerical and free-text feedback on specific performance indicators from juniors, peers, seniors, nursing and allied health, i.e. 360 degrees. An example: https://t.co/4HNzcmlSXu

The multi-source feedback (MSF) process is a valuable way for trainees to identify specific areas for improvement. It is also a CPD activity for Australian consultant anaesthetists. #MedTwitter, does your program / college use MSF, particularly once training is completed?

How does allelic heterogeneity work in practice with multiple haplotypes and alleles? How does that interact with GxE effects? and the phenotypes here are analogous - perhaps even "orthologous" - to human phenotypes - Heart beat. Height/Length. Fear response.

So - how much variance in a phenotype is due to structured environment (eg, temperature, calorie intact) vs "impossible to measure" environmental variation? Are there GxE effects? Do you need an allelic or a genotypic model to fit them well?

In human studies one can argue, speculate and then ultimately... use simple, robust models. We can never really change or challenge this approach. But - in Medaka fish, which is just as good a vertebrate as humans - we can specifically explore all these things.

This goes from the routine - do you fit a genotype model or an allelic model - to sophisticated - What about compound het / allelic hetreogenity - local GxG, or are GxE effects likely to be present on allele basis or a specific genotype?

We tend to choose the simplest models which are adequate (which is fine) and even in nested models, good modelling often does not want to "spend" information/model on the rare events. However, in the "tails" of these simpler models is precisely where we want to be accurate

These are key concepts in human studies but we nearly always have to infer this via statistical models in observational studies ("cohort studies") - we cannot by definition easily challenge or test or explore these models as the models do the inference.
I get a real tingle about being able to *explore* and *test* key aspects of phenotype in this system, such as the impact structured environment, GxE and just understanding variance in phenotypes.

We have done the genome sequencing and have initial intensive phenotyping happening - it is clear this will be a very powerful system. As a postdoc you will lead the analysis of these, and be co-first author on resulting papers.

(In mammalian terms this is a bit like RILs - eg, BxD lines or Collaborative Cross in mice; but unlike these populations the variation in the MIKK panel really looks like it is drawn from the wild Medaka population - ie, looks more like human genetics)

Using this we've set up the first vertebrate wild-derived inbred panel (the MIKK panel). Mapping this to human genetics, it is as if we are able to replicate a *population* of individuals in a studies again and again. This is common place in Arabidopsis and Drosophila

Medaka fish are japanese rice paddy fish, and we work closely with @Naruse_kiyoshi from NIBB in Nagoya Japan. Medaka are unique in vertebrates in that there is a protocol to inbreed individuals from the wild which is successful in around 1 in 2 attempts.

At the same time, we know many factors that facilitate #SARSCoV2 transmission: * high density * indoors * poor ventilation * loud speaking and singingThese factors are likely better guidance than tracing statistics (at least in many countries).

While household transmissions are important and easy to trace, they are also very hard to prevent. And every household transmission starts with an infection outside the household. Don't use this as an argument for inaction.
Whether transmission in restaurants, bars, private gatherings, etc are captured likely depends a lot on the test-and-trace strategy and effort.

The @rki_de publishes a fairly detailed breakdown of known transmission settings and households account for a big chunk. But households are among the easiest to trace, while public transport, shopping, etc are essentially impossible. https://t.co/YSPDPMP8t0

For another good take, including observations on what's not in this paper (inter-host transmission experiments), see @angie_rasmussen's thread: https://t.co/8jZuobavM0 6/6

Which brings me to this sobering sentence from the paper: "All of the COVID-19 vaccines currently in clinical trials are based on the original D614 spike sequence". The authors' experiments suggest that they should still work against G614, but only time will tell. 5/n

And same has happened to the virus population around the world. D variant is now almost extinct in the UK: last example from @CovidGenomicsUK was > 1 month ago, during which time we have posted >17,000 G seqs. (Less data in other countries, but pattern is the same globally) 4/n

And I think that reveals an easy to overlook point about evolution: even a tiny selective advantage is unstoppable given enough generations to be applied. Once the G variant appears somewhere (in this case, cells in a dish), it rapidly dominates. 3/n

There's an interesting contrast between a small absolute difference of D vs G (Fig 1c, below left) and a striking competitive difference. When infecting cells with a 9:1 ratio of D to G, the G still rapidly takes over (Fig 3g, below right) 2/n https://t.co/edHfoamDxv

When they make this informed choice, they are no longer patients but participants, participating in the journey of discovery and part of the solution.Read the full post:https://t.co/7zW3mmdGjj
Patients certainly do not choose to have COVID-19, they do not choose to be isolated from their loved ones, but they can choose to help find a better treatment.
Patients have a right to choose to be involved in finding and trying new treatments; in many ways this may be the best form of autonomy that can be offered to them.

Without trials, new and potentially lifesaving treatments cannot properly be determined.Whilst patients feel understandably cautious about trying new therapies, the safest way to do so is under the careful observation of a clinical trial

Offering participation in a clinical trial requires a change in communication style for the medical teamthere must be a confession that for this illness there is a limitation of medical knowledge and treatment options

Patients may already feel disoriented in this strange environment, shunned, and separatedDeciding to participate in a clinical trial may be daunting if you are unable to talk it over in person with family and friends

patients may not find it easy to connect with hospital staff. Voices are muffled by the layers of PPE, facial expressions are hidden behind masksIt is here on the isolation ward that patients may be offered participation in a clinical trial

Some highlights:The COVID-19 isolation ward is a somewhat surreal placeMost patients who need to be admitted to hospital feel quite unwellAll staff entering the room are covered in personal protective equipment (PPE)

SNPs under primers are something we need to watch as the virus mutates. I think this is a smaller problem right now but needs to be considered when looking at re-infection data. To understand these have a look at an EUA for the Roche qPCR assay. FDA RUO for Roche as an example

If you have 1 copy on that swab and you only take 1/50th of the volume into qPCR.. you have a poisson sampling problem are unlikely to find the single molecule unless 50 tests are performed. This can create false negatives. SNPs under primers can create false negatives as well.

Sampling limitations.LODs are measured putting RNA straight into the qPCR. Reality requires qPCR of a nasal swab usually soaked into 1ml of fluid and no-one PCRs the whole milliliter. They take 1/25th - 1/50th of this into the qPCR.

In the image classification example, the neural network architecture already knows things like edge detection, color gradients, and what objects look like in general. So what general knowledge should our psychiatry deep learning models have? #WCPG2020
The real advantage of transfer learning is that because you are building on top of the neural network‚Äôs pre-trained know-how, it takes far less data and computing power to train it on a new task.

A pedagogical example of transfer learning is taking a neural network that can classify objects (‚Äúdog‚Äù, ‚Äúbicycle‚Äù, ‚Äúphone‚Äù) and retraining it to distinguish between more specific classes of something (like ‚Äúdog breed‚Äù or ‚Äúmodel of car‚Äù).

ResNet34 is an image recognition neural network architecture. One of the biggest advances in machine learning is using a pre-trained neural network and then fine tuning it for a new task (‚Äútransfer learning‚Äù).

However, there's a community of independent plant breeders working to breed sweet potatoes to produce seed more reliably. This is a first step to allow more rapid breeding of the crop, to increase the diversity of varieties adapted to different places.

In conclusion: now, in the middle of a pandemic, with a viral disease that can be fatal, and even if it isn't, seems to cause long term damage, is a gym essential? No. Is mental health an important topic that needs many resources? Yes. Are these the same issue right now? No.

If mental health is the biggest concern, let's look at mental health services, like psychologists, GP's, hotlines etc. A gym is not meant to replace these, nor should you ever let anybody tell you that fresh air or exercise can be a replacement for these essential services.

Staying open puts the members and coaches at risk. For those now almost permanently WFH that the thought of a gym closing down, when it is the only time you get to get out and feel good, is daunting and upsetting, and I wish it wasn't the case. But right now it is safest.

And our desire to reduce cognitive dissonance applies to the other therapies tested in SOLIDARITY - e.g., hydroxychloroquine.And to other issues with COVID

Once a practice has become somewhat entrenched, it becomes hard to reverse ‚Äì even with strong new evidence. I wonder where we would all stand if SOLIDARITY results had come first (together with SIMPLE JAMA and the China Lancet study), and a few months later ACTT-1?

Would I still prescribe remdesivir ? I think I would for patients early in their disease and requiring O2 ‚Äì being open with patients that it may get them out of hospital earlier, but it probably doesn‚Äôt reduce their risk of dying. Noting this helps reduce my cognitive dissonance.

For those who have never been convinced about remdesivir and those who may not have had access, there is less cognitive dissonance in now seeing data that there is no benefit in reducing mortality. These results affirm a prior belief.

The SOLIDARITY results have generated a cognitive dissonance for me. A dissonance reduced if I can find sub-groups that benefit (those needing O2), or in explaining why SOLIDARITY was a lower quality study (patient and healthcare heterogeneity, no data on time from symptoms).

For myself, I have invested in prescribing remdesivir, in efforts to prioritise patients and applying to our national medicine stockpile scheme, in telling patients they will receive the best antiviral medication available, in giving talks saying that it works.

Those who have used remdesivir, participated in clinical trials, seen patients improve while receiving it ‚Äì we are more likely to highlight the gains seen in ACTT-1 and the weaknesses of SOLIDARITY.
My thoughts about remdesivir and SOLIDARITY:There was no overall benefit in reducing mortality for remdesivir. But our prior biases are important in assessing the SOLIDARITY results.

As ever this sentiment is all too easy to tweet and far far harder to deliver; there are plenty of places to point to substantial improvements but we need to push - and achieve - more.

Controlling infection is a binary thing (formally: R at 1ish or lower, or R significantly above 1). We're actually not that far away from these levels; in the UK context we should strive for maximal operational efficiency of TTI to minimise the need for harsher NPIs.

So, due to both with LongCOVID being present at some rate and the rightful deep societal dislike of preventable deaths there is no other approach in my mind than controlling the infection rate until a vaccine emerges which is, probably, not that far away

Back to the right wing press. I get the civil liberties side and desire for individual responsibility; I get the lives vs livelihoods conceptual debate though far prefer the lives vs lives framing. BUT this virus has certain properties which one cannot magic away with arguments

Can a well functioning TTI get us through winter? It's tough to know, and one should watch Germany here carefully, but one needs to frame this I think the other way around - what regional and national "blanket" NPIs do we need to have to keep infection rates under control

(it is worth noting that in March and April Japan navigated the first "wave" largely without deep testing, but with excellent tracing in particular back-tracing to site+time of infection. This leverages the overdispersion of the virus spread, well explained by @AdamJKucharski )

Details are: who do you ask to isolate? When do you ask people to get tests? which information is most important to ask for testing and isolation? All of this has been brought together in the most coherent way in my view in Japan.

Again, this is somewhat about big picture stuff (local vs central, but note some quite localised systems don't work well as they could as well as centralised systems) but there are lots and lots of details

One can look at Germany, Denmark, Austria and Japan (and they are all not perfect as people in those countries will attest) and use it simply to berate the operations in your own country (UK, FR, ES, NL ...) but I prefer to focus on what it tells us about what one can do better.

No matter what your big picture strategy is, everyone wants the best possible TTI operations - noone says for this pandemic "ok, I think we can accept a lower delivery of TTI". They might have not funded or organised it well, but its pretty much part of every strategy.

There is a huge tendency in my view to focus on big-scale cultural aspects which are different between countries, rather than the detailed, operational aspects of delivering TTI (or FTTIS if you prefer).

The weather getting worse (and colder) means we've got a further slope to get over. On this background, you can clearly see that German and some extent Danish and Austrian approaches worked deeper operationally. This also corresponds to South Korea and Japan's approach.

The pretty consistent rise in cases across Europe points to me to as much weather issues as well as changes in social contacts post summer holidays across Europe; the change in timings in countries means it must also be societal contact changes as well.

We know the virus. We know its incubation period and onward transmission rate in the absence of interventions. We know that transmission is overdispersed. We know much more about the pathway that leads to (sadly) death, and more about what we can do to mitigate it.

Yet, almost without exception, (i) will be the answer to this and many similar "admin" issues across the hundreds of universities in the UK.Why? I really don't know.
Yes you might need to pay a developer to do it, but the time savings are huge, as you save thousands of hours of academic/HR time every year (across a large University)

(iii) of course the best option is to make the system do it. It's not hard - enter the criteria into an actual HR IT system and have that same system automatically generate the forms. This has been possible for decades. It's not complex

(ii) is the second worst option. On a per-hour basis your HR person probably costs less than your academic PI, therefore it makes sense purely on money grounds to make the HR person do it. You might have to employ more of them, but the cost savings in academic time compensates

(i) is objectively the worst option. In a modern university, academic PIs are your money winners. You want them spending their time teaching (student income), researching (research income), or publishing (REF income).Plus you probably pay them more than the HR person.

Now, someone has to copy those "essential criteria" and "desirable criteria" from the job description into the candidate forms.There are three options: (i) the PI does it; (ii) the HR person does it; (iii) the system does it

After interviews, we have to score each candidate against these "essential criteria" and "desirable criteria".This takes place in a Word form - one for each candidate interviewed.And it is provided BLANK.
This may be unique to Edinburgh, but I doubt it.Here, when we advertise a job, we need to write "essential criteria" and "desirable criteria".These go into the job description.

By definition a number of these decisions have to be reactivity (ideally; there is an agreed framework which one moves through with decision points have clear criteria, but honestly, it is super-complex down there).

3.  "U-turn" framing of decision making. I appreciate consistency in decision making is a good thing and show competence, but in this situation which is both complex and changes, we should *expect* decisions.

I note the comment from @segal_eran from Israel, helping to navigate the 2nd wave, that trying to manage to a healthcare capacity is not the right mindset - it is whether one is in control (R ~1 or less) or out of control (R higher than 1).

2. Hospitalisation rates across the UK being very low vs March. This is mistakes the concerns about growth vs absolute, and importantly once you get into hospitalisation growth there is a lot of momentum in the system (infections, incubation etc).
1. False positives. These are well handled in the system - they are present but managed well.
Some things that make considerable twitter noise but I don't think is worth too much attention:

Again, there is little benefit in a "corona-olympics" mindset (who is doing better than who); what's more important is working out what works (and doesn't work); Germany and Italy stand out here to me, and in both cases it is the trace side where I think we can learn most.

Zooming out, it is worth noting that now a substantial number of European countries have high, probably unsustainable infection rates - the combination of weather and change of interaction patterns presumably.
On the other side, Wales seems to be showing how to get on top of infections from my 10,000 meter view from the stats, with infections going down in many regions (as well as up in others).
Two contrasts: Northern Ireland's infection rate has had a scary increase over the last 3 weeks - I am glad they are seriously considering a circuit breaker crude NPI ("lockdown").

It is notable that how regional the intensity of this second wave is; underlying reasons are complex (likely include: starting infection levels; ease of isolation / WFH; household density / population density; student population levels)

Again the fact that *some* things are working and there is more potential in the system does not magically mean one can make this work (it is far far easier to tweet / write columns about this than actually *do it* in my view).

Secondly it is clear some things in TTI are working - testing capacity is high (turn around time can - I hope will - get better); it is trace and isolation where I think we have more headroom in the UK.
(Just knowing what is going on is not the same as taking decisions which changes infection rates)

Firstly, a reminder that we are in a different place in terms of testing/surveillance - so we are (rightly) having decisions+discussions far earlier as infections rise. This is a good, not a bad thing, but by itself doesn't make these decisions any easier.

Rather than entering that debate with partial and less well sourced information (I trust Patrick Vallance + Chris Whitty and the SAGE system to provide a reasoned menu of options to policy/decision makers; I don't envy anyone in this decision chain) here are some observations:

What the UK - or more accurately England, Wales, Scotland and NI - should do in the next weeks for Coronavirus is complex, but that complexity should not be something to hide behind; no decisions are decisions in this deeply unhappy world.

All of this happened almost a year to the day from when we found out my 3yo son had a large tumor in his spine. I'm grateful we figured out how sick he was and that now he's in a good spot and has a high likelihood of good outcomes, but it's been a really jarring week.

One of the doctors said he's been doing this for 30 years and has only seen a few hearts worse than his. They were pretty amazed by how high functioning he was. They said he had a 40% chance of death without intervention over the next 12 months.

Last Thurs the doctors recommended he be immediately placed on the transplant list and they expect he'll get a heart w/in 3 months. They released him from the hospital, but he has to be on IV meds until he gets a transplant - they said he can't be off them from longer than 5 mins

Last Monday he went for a short run then him and my mom went in for one final test. They tested his cardiac function and his central venous pressure was 17 (should be 3-8) and his cardiac output was 2.28 liters/min (should be 4-8). They immediately hospitalized him.

In February he took a turn for the worse and started having a lot of edema, feeling really crappy, and most shockingly being mostly unable to run - only 1-2 miles at a time compared to the 4-8 he was doing every day before February.

Two weeks ago my dad went to Mayo clinic in AZ to have his heart failure assessed. He's had heart failure for ~10 years but has been very high functioning and stable. His been an endurance running his whole life  and ran a 3 hour marathon after his diagnosis.

Selecting every year, with contaminating pollen, will eventually move the population in the direction you want. It will take much longer though.

We are excited about this because metformin would be a cheap, well-studied treatment for those PD cases associated with hyperactivated neuronal mitochondria, and simple screens like this in worms have potential to uncover new therapeutics.

To our surprise, the top suppressor of curling was metformin, the common diabetes drug. (We had just thrown it into the screen for fun, really.) Metformin suppressed neurodegeneration, likely due to the lower OCR and less oxidative damage. https://t.co/gfQWHqW1WH
Just submitted a #ctenophore paper! Probs going to be rejected from my auspicious journal choice, but time for üçï anyway to celebrate.

Danielle & Salman Sohrabi carried out a screen of FDA-approved drugs (more on his automation of this screen  soon). To mimic a clinical situation, they knocked down bcat-1 through mid-adulthood, when curling begins, and then fed the worms heat-killed bacteria plus the drugs.
Could there be other drugs that might also ‚Äúrescue‚Äù bcat-1(-)-induced PD-like phenotypes?

So we wondered, what if we slowed the mitochondria down? Danielle treated the bcat-1(RNAi) worms with a very low dose of azide, and indeed, the treated worms curled less and had significantly less neurodegeneration. https://t.co/x4IR5VEyxc

Since this BCAT acts in mitochondria and these enzymes are all in the mitochondria, she then looked at neuronal mitochondrial activity-and found that they are hyperactive, with increased oxygen consumption rates. This correlated with higher rates of damaged proteins in neurons.

To see what was going on in these neurons, Danielle did neuronal transcriptomics and metabolomics (with Vrinda Kali and Gary Miller), and found that genes regulating glycolysis and the TCA cycle are actually UPREGULATED by bcat-1 knockdown, and TCA cycle metabolite depletion. https://t.co/GUrJpdfPsq

You can come from any country in the world, but we have a particular affinity and responsibility to take on students from EMBL member states. Do apply! (Deadline next Tuesday, 13th October). https://t.co/Bk1XWLKzkv

My best work often happens with my students (waves at @ettwiller, @BenedictPaten, @michaelhoffman, @dzerbino , @HannahVMeyer  @swtimmer who are on twitter) - and I learn as much as you do over the PhD!

You will be part of @embl's excellent PhD program (called predocs in EMBL speak) - you start with a 3-month course in Heidelberg about molecular biology (often helped by heferweisen and exploration of Neckar valley) and would join my lab day-to-day in December 2021 or Jan 2022

Over your PhD I hope you will develop your own directions inside my own broad research group direction. There's plenty to do here (so many things), and plenty of options for setting your own agenda by the end of your PhD.

I have a maximum of three students at any time, usually two, and then a number of postdocs usually in collaborations with groups such as @WittbrodtLab, @EBIgoldman, @MoritzGerstung and others. There will be a selection of starting projects that you might like

My interest often comes back to fundamental algorithms in DNA sequence analysis and at the moment there is a rich seam to look into around @nanopore, both in modification calling/biology and funky new approaches on adaptive sampling.

I have a small but perfectly formed research group which I co-run with @tomaswfitz; we focus on outbred genetics in both Japanese Rice Paddy fish (Medaka fish) and Humans (a very interesting organism for all sorts of reasons!).

It may be of interesting to note in the context of #COVID19  that while existentialism tends to represent the moral values generally associated to 'modern Western culture', essentialism is more in line with those traditionally associated to 'Far Eastern philosophy'.6/

Essentialism in its political form can be defined as: "The doctrine that states that there is a single nature and destiny for human kind and that an elite is indispensable for bringing this about through political action." Hugh P. McDonald5/https://t.co/DB8nEp5XnN

Existentialism, in short, both in its atheistic and religious expressions, recognises an individual person as a free and responsible agent determining their own development through acts of the will, which gives meaning to life.4/

It feels interesting to speculate along what axis our societies may become polarised in the future. I would predict the major new divide in society will crystallise along the 'existentialist vs. essentialist' axis that currently divides society on how to respond to #COVID19.3/
The dissonance and internal inconstencies on all sides of the political spectrum within our societies may have become too strong for current tribalisms to survive much beyond the pandemic. 2/

One intriguing aspect of the #COVID19 pandemic is the extent to which it has exposed current ideologies such as the current left-right divide for their hollow tribalism, rather than carriers of shared moral values. 1/

It seems this particular case is the latter, in which case going on the attack isn't a great strategy.Anyways, regardless- this sort of thing *always* brings out the worst in atheist twitter. And while it doesn't do much to break down Christian cultural dominance...

As for ID in particular- yes, it's part of an insidious narrative pushed by evangelicals to make their young-earth creationism more palatable.*but* since it's intentionally meant to deceive, people can fail to realize the connotations. In this case, intent *does* matter.

Sure, these religions have their own issues to talk about internally, but they aren't part of the dominant US religious culture that causes harmDemanding non-Christians apologize for Christians only reinforces Christian cultural dominance, by making it synonymous w religion

But demanding that, say, a Jewish or Muslim or Hindu person apologize for the harms of a specific portion of Christianity, when they are also harmed by those same people, is really unfair, and not nearly as woke as you think it sounds.

Again, this is homogenizing a whole lot of things together. Does the progressive Christian community need to have a conversation about how their faith is so often used to hurt marginalized people? Absolutely, 100%.
Now, to change course slightly: a common argument, especially among former evangelicals, is "well religion hurt me, so religious people broadly need to apologize for that".
To be clear, white evangelicals (and Christians more broadly) aren't persecuted, but ooh boy do they clamor for any shred that they can use to claim they are.

Furthermore, lumping every religion in together into an overarching "science vs religion" cage match does nothing to help science, but is a big part of building the persecution narrative that white evangelicalism gets so much fuel from.

As many others have pointed out, assuming that being "religious" is synonymous with the way this loud, angry segment of white evangelicals is ends up particularly excluding scientists of other religions, *especially* BIPOC scientists.
Homogenizing every faith and belief system into a single monolithic category of "Religion" isn't just inaccurate, either- it's harmful.
I can only speak to my admittedly narrow experience- but there are lots of religious expressions where this just isn't a major force.

Sure, you see this sort of thing in other religions, other places and times.But it's by no means a given, and isn't inevitable any more than a non-religious philosophy being used in a similarly toxic way.
So notice something here?This isn't so much a history of "religion" per se as it is of a very specific melding of white supremacist politics and a particular type of white evangelicals.
This political movement thrives off a deep-seated antagonism with anything smacking of change. There's one true way to do things, both in the church and in society at large.
For a whole lot of reasons- a big one being angry racist white people tend to stick together politically speaking- the right-wing bloc remained, and eventually became ascendant

A lot of modern Christian fundamentalism grows out of this period- lots of angry white people who are looking for ways to back up their racism, sexism, xenophobia, and general hatred of the various social reform movement.
You see lots of abolitionists and, later on, progressives, using Christianity to back up their calls for social reform.But that didn't go over well with everyone.

There are two points we should all be able to agree on. First, #COVID19 is a very severe crisis but not the end times. Second, demonising those who disagree with us will only postpone the return to our 'normal' post-pandemic lives.6/

The #COVID19 pandemic will be over eventually, probably sooner than many believe. We need to get to the other end of it with the lowest possible morbidity and mortality, but also with our sanity, society and institutions reasonably intact.5/

Besides being uniformed, the claim that there will be no return to normality is deeply unhelpful in terms of public health. Such a prospect is unacceptable to a large fraction of the population, and undermines trust, engagement and participation in public health interventions.4/

There is no straightforward solution how to deal with #COVID19, or any other pandemic, but a series of difficult and painful tradeoffs. Unsurprisingly, such a situation leads to disagreements on the best course of action, including amongst the most qualified.3/

#COVID19 is not the first pandemic and probably not the last. Over the last 100 years, humanity had to deal with influenza 1957, 1968, 2009, Cholera 1899‚Äì1923; Cholera 1961‚Äì75; the plague 3rd pandemic 1855-1960 and HIV/AIDS. Each time 'normality' resumed.2/

Ultimately, this paper has helpful and interesting findings for microbiome researchers, but essentially no (immediate) utility for the public: 7 carefully screened babies in Finland had their microbiomes modified in a way that was not immediately harmful, that's all. 14/end

The point is, there are multiple, hugely important logical leaps being made in the Independent article that just aren't supported by the research paper, which, again, did not attempt to look at *whether babies were actually helped by the procedure.* 13/

People with eczema already have Roseomonas on their skin, but theirs doesn't behave the same way. It messes with signaling pathways that cause inflammation. Spraying the misbehaving version of Roseomonas on skin actually made eczema worse. "Species" isn't the relevant factor. 12/

In short, there's a skin microbe called "Roseomonas mucosa" that, when sprayed onto the skin, can dramatically alleviate symptoms of eczema, even better than drugs can. HOWEVER, it only works if the Roseomonas is first taken from the skin of a *healthy donor.* 11/
There are plenty of examples where even species-level information doesn't get at the real problems. This paper from a few weeks ago has one of many examples of why: https://t.co/TP0eP2iL1L 10/

The problem is that this study was not about whether the C-section babies were less sick. We have no idea. We can make their microbiomes look more like the microbiomes of babies delivered vaginally, but counting species and comparing bar graphs doesn't tell the whole story. 9/

There's conflicting evidence, but the issue pops up among babies who are delivered via C-section‚Äîthey consistently have different microbiome composition than babies delivered vaginally. So if we can "fix" the microbiome of C-section babies, maybe they won't be as sick. 8/

The primary reason this question is important is because there's reason to believe that the infant gut microbiome could be linked to all kinds of autoimmune diseases, so being able to modify that microbiome COULD be helpful. 7/

The experiment is exclusively concerned with one question: Can we use fecal transplants to alter the gut microbiome of babies? The answer is yes, at least for about three months, according to data from SEVEN BABIES. 6/

The other reason this @Independent article is irresponsible is because it states the treatment "may help to strengthen immune system." There is NOTHING in the paper to support this. Not because it's a bad paper, but because that wasn't even the question being asked. 5/

In very specific contexts, fecal microbiota transplants can save lives, but there are lots of ways they can go wrong. This is the main reason it's dangerous to write an article about "giving poop to babies is good!"‚Äîmost of the time, it's not. 4/

The babies that got the microbiome transplants were fine, but only after MORE than half of the mothers were excluded from the study because their microbiome samples were too dangerous to put into a human: 29% had pathogens, plus others with herpes and "suspected hepatitis." 3/

First, here's the link to the paper, because they didn't include it. You'll see the TITLE specifically states it's a "proof-of-concept study," which in this context means essentially, "If we do this to a baby, do they get killed by E. coli?" 2/ https://t.co/EgU4BK2Luh

Headline: "Feeding C-section newborns mother's faeces may help to strengthen immune system, study suggests." You may be wondering: Is this true? No! Let's examine, because I think @Independent did kind of a bad job here. 1/ https://t.co/dbKndcz5tn
